Despite the difficult operating environment characterised by increased competition and influx of substitute propositions, Dairy giant FrieslandCampina WAMCO Nigeria Plc achieved strong volume and value growth. The company yesterday announced that its turnover increased by 35 per cent from N199.5 billion in 2020 to N268.4 billion in 2021. At its 49th Annual General Meeting (AGM) in Lagos the company also said  its operating profit  increased by 13 per cent from N19.4 billion in 2020 to N22 billion last year. However, high finance costs due to Naira devaluation led to a decline in Profit Before Tax (PBT) by 15 per cent from N14.9 billion in 2020 to N12.7 billion in 2021. Subsequently, in accordance with the company’s dividend policy, the Board of Directors proposed a total dividend of N5.83 per N0.50 ordinary share.   13% MPR: Interest rate may rise above 30%     Naira falls across markets     Lagos, Kano lead 82.73m NIN enrolment   An interim dividend of N1.10 was paid in 2021, and a final cash dividend of N4.23per N0.50 share was approved by the shareholders at the AGM. A bonus share will also be issued to existing shareholders on a one-for-one basis i.e., one ordinary share with a nominal value of N0.50 for each share owned. Managing Director, FrieslandCampina WAMCO Nigeria Plc and Sub-Sahara Africa Cluster, Ben Langat, said: “In the year under review, we made excellent progress in strengthening our business strategies. “We scaled up investments in brands and optimised physical availability. The combination of solid brands, operational excellence and expanded route-to-market (RTM) distribution strategy sustained our leadership position and delivered significant top-line growth.”